Jason Furman had a very good presentation that touched on the same issue I've been banging on about: if you stories about growth depend on foreign capital, don't ignore the price

So the GOP is trying to use lies to ram through a tax bill that rewards the idle rich at workers' expense -- and that's a fairly distant third among the bad things they're up to right now. Truly, this is hell, nor are we out of it.
The Tax Foundation Has Some Explaining To Do

Simple request for Tax Foundation: what does your model of Senate bill say about impact on trade deficit and U.S. net international investment income? Don't say it isn't modeled. You can't do a model that relies crucially on global capital without addressing these questions.
So there are multiple, layered reasons not to believe anything about this Tax Foundation analysis 5/
And this would be temporary -- people would expect the dollar to come down eventually, reducing rates of return and slowing the inflow even further. The long run would be very long 4/

And even running the required deficit over a decade would mean trade deficit of ~3% of GDP per year (over and above baseline). This would among other things require something like a 30% stronger dollar 3/

The counterpart of those inflows would be trade deficits of equal size. TF model seems to claim most effects in first year -- which is impossible. The US *cannot* run a one-year trade deficit of >20% of GDP -- not enough traded goods. 3/

But we should note a further problem. This study claims growth of GDP of around 3 percent from corporate tax cut, presumably by drawing in foreign capital. At a rate of return of, say, 10% that means inflows of 30% of GDP 2/
Republicans are rushing to cite the Tax Foundation study claiming huge growth effects from tax cuts. It has problems even on its own assumptions 1/

All in all, then, big corporate tax cuts are likely to be anti-growth, not pro-growth *even using the arguments Trump and allies are making for those cuts*. We're not even talking about fairness here, just growth arithmetic done right 9/
The Video Game Engine in Your Head
How Our Brains Play Angry Birds With The World By Eric Jaffe , via

And this doesn't even take account of the impact on deficits. Deficit spending can boost growth if the economy is well below full employment, or if it's used to finance productive public investment. But this tax cut would just cause crowding out 8/

Playing around with the numbers, I find it easy to come up with scenarios in which this windfall is bigger than the taxes collected on new capital inflows. In that case the corporate tax cut actually *reduces* US national income 7/

This is very unlikely to be more than a fraction of a percent of GDP, even after a decade. But wait, there's more: unless the tax cut is fully passed through to wages -- which won't happen -- foreign capital already in the US gets a big windfall 6/

So where's the net gain to the US? It comes from the tax wedge: foreign capital pays part of its return to the U.S. Treasury. That's it for small capital inflows. And that means that only 20-35% of the gain in GDP (effective v nominal tax rate) is net gain to US income 5/

"reputation" is Swift trying to grow while trying to keep what inherently makes her Taylor. I think she succeeded. Is the album, "1989"? No, but not many are. It's another strong performance from Ms. Swift, and a personal narrative that she should not want to be excluded from.

15. "New Year's Day"

- The epilogue of "reputation." This song could be on any Swift album, and that's the point. Taylor tried a new persona, a darker one, on this album but she's still the girl she's always been. She's new yet nostalgic. A very pretty, sad song. A good goodbye.

14. "Call It What You Want"

- Okay, big finish. This is by far the best song on the album and quintessential Taylor. If "reputation" is all about trying to get people to really know and see the person Taylor is, this song is the exclamation point. A sweet and strong pop song.

13. "This Is Why We Can't Have Nice Things"

- Not a fan. It's likely about Ye, and ok fine, whatever. Drama. But the song itself jumps up and down and is too goofy for me. Probably my least favorite song on the album.

11. "Dancing With Our Hands Tied"

- I like the chorus on this one. The more I listen to this album the more I hear an artist really trying to recover. Also, 11 tracks in and this track by track review is getting exhausting.

10. "King of My Heart"

- This song is really all over the place, so I'm kinda meh about it. Again, it's interesting to hear Tay talking about her end game when it comes to relationships. I don't know if she's sure when that'll be, but this song is hoping it's soon. So-so track.

9. "Getaway Car"

- Another fun one with a good hook. This might be about Tom Hiddleston, but who really knows? But it's another song about Tay trying to figure out on how to make initial, fantastical, and quite drunken love last forever. Hey Tay, if you figure that out, LMK.

8. "Gorgeous"

- Without a doubt, the most fun song on this whole album. It's playful, it's goofy, it's old school T. Swift. I also enjoy the dynamic of Taylor trying to fall in love, but accepting a life of stumbling home alone to her cats (again, been there). Fun all around.

7. "So It Goes..."

- Not a huge fan of this one. It's too dour. However, Tay conveying that she's "not a bad girl, but does bad things" is interesting to consider. The song itself is a bit weak for me despite its interesting questions about the artist singing it.

6. "Look What You Made Me Do"

- Hoo boy. Listen, this song isn't THAT bad, but it definitely has issues. It's grown on me, but it has the feel of an AIM profile written by someone who is reinventing themselves in high school. The video is better. Welp, another day, another drama

5. "Delicate"

- Tay understands that letting someone in requires them seeing you clearly. I think this album is about her realization that maybe no one really does right now. "You must like me for me," but who are you? That's what this album is really about. Fun synthesized song

4. "Don't Blame Me"

- A reason I've always liked Tay is I believe she's in desperate need of love, but is so bad at getting/keeping it (been there). "Blame Me" compares love to a drug, and that's what it's been to her and probably what it'll always be. A good, but not great song

3. "I Did Something Bad"

- Dark Taylor in full effect, and I'm here for it. There's swearing, anger, and implication! Tay is scorching earth here and it's deserved. The line, "This is how the world works. You gotta leave before you get left" shows that Tay ain't a kid anymore.

Start with a CD1-trained RBM that gets -125 nats on MNIST (,). Compute the data-conditional moments. Train a PCD RBM to match them. It gets -86, comparable to PCD from scratch. Conclusion: CD1 learns good features, and only screws up global mass allocation.
Interestingly, Variational Walkback (,) is based on the same reverse annealing procedure and variational bound as RAISE (,). RBMs are still relevant!

But reporter , challenged the depiction of council papers as "neutral, objective and only the facts; which inform people what's going on in their areas and nothing else". 
"That's just not true ... they are also a chance for councils to publish unfettered PR"

A council newspaper 'talks about services, provides information and it's penetration is much bigger [than local press]. Unless you have a freesheet going through every door, I don't see there's any alternative', said
But he also said Hackney Today, and other council newspapers, now have more legitimacy post-Grenfell, citing ,'s call for local authorities to be more in touch with the people they serve
He told students 'if statutory notices didn't legally have to be published in a paper, we wouldn't publish [Hackney Today]. It's as simple as that. It wouldn't be viable'
Glanville added that Hackney Today was full of "micro detail" that wouldn't appear in the local press unless you paid for it as advertising
These comments were made by ,, who defended the council's paper during debate with our reporter , held at Goldsmiths last month
He suggested some local media housing issues had been "alarmist in some cases" where as Hackey Today, the council paper, had been "factual, inviting people to public meetings"

Glanville said a challenge post-Grenfell is 'how councils communicate with their residents. You cannot do that just through the prism of the local press. If you want to land quite complex issues like fire safety you can't talk about it enough...
